<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06220265 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06220265 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; FOOD; SERVICE; PARK; LIST; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Kit Flores's four kids, age 4, 5, 6, and 8, chowed down on pepperoni pizza,salad and fresh strawberries last week on the lawn of San Jose's Backesto Park-- compliments of the U.S. Department of Agriculture.;    The USDA-fundedsummer food service program, sponsored by the San Jose Unified SchoolDistrict, is offering free lunches Monday through Friday until Aug. 16 tochildren in needy areas in San Jose, said Barbara Rouse, assistant director offood services for the school district. The service is also available in MorganHill, Gilroy, San Martin and Alviso.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PIZZA IN THE PARKSCHOOL LUNCH PROGRAM DELIVERS EVEN IN SUMMER  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this articleAlso ran in EX4/1  </MEMO><TEXT>     According to Rouse, the nationwide program is aimed at low-income childrenunder 18 years of age who receive federally subsidized meals during the schoolyear, but who might go hungry for lunch during the months of summer vacation.;   In the San Jose Unified School District, where the food service has beenused for over 10 years, 10,300 children, or one in every three students,receive subsidized breakfasts and lunches.;    Through the program, boxedlunches are transported in vans to local community centers and parks likeBackesto, where parents and their children sometimes line up an hourbeforehand to receive the meals.;    Flores, who has been using the programsince last summer said the free lunches have helped her family cope with hardeconomic times.;    &quot;My husband's in real estate and (the lunches) come inreal handy because we're not making a lot of money,&quot; Flores said.;    Anothermother who was at the park with her two children, age 6 and 9, agreed.;    &quot;Itdoes (help) because I work only during the school year,&quot; said the woman, aninstructional associate with the San Jose Unified School District who declinedto give her name.;    Until school starts again in the fall, the woman saidher family must make ends meet on her husband's income alone. &quot;It gets prettytight during the summer months,&quot; she said.;    The San Jose woman said shedoesn't use the program regularly, but her kids like to come to the park ondays when pizza or chicken nuggets are served. &quot;They always make me look atthe menu,&quot; she said with a laugh. &quot;They really look forward to it because youbring a blanket and it's like a picnic.&quot;; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; For moreinformation on the program, call the San Jose Unified School District's foodservice office at (408) 998-6021.; Lunch schedule; Following is a list oflunch sites in San Jose. The program will continue through Aug. 16.;  Site                Address; Backesto Park         13th and Empire streets; OlinderCenter        16th and Williams streets; Roosevelt Center      901 E. SantaClara St.; Solari Center         3590 Cas Drive; Gardner Center        520 W.Virginia St.; Watson Center         1082 Jackson St.; Christopher Elementary;School (YMCA)         565 Coyote Road; Mosquito Action Club  81 N. 9th St.;Source: San Jose Unified School District; Mercury News  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LISA CHEN, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910807  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  488  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday August 7, 199100220265,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>